entry.title: Project Report
entry.summary:
Project Report¶

Our problem as stated in the propectus¶

Our problem was to look at the closing stock prices of 12 different nations around the world, including the US, and see how fluctuations in these prices depended on one another. Specifically, we wanted to look at the relation between US stocks and stocks from foreign nations.

Our data sources, their format, and the difficulties to get them¶

Our data came in the form of 12 timeseries. Retrieving them was very simple using the Pandas method DataReader, which is compatible with the Yahoo Finance API

Main challenge¶

Narrowing down the large amount of data into smaller data sets from which we could extract meaningful comparisons.

Our Findings¶

Measuring the Dependence of Each Country on Other Countries¶

  • There is a pattern that export-orientated economics (Cancada, Germany, Sweden, Taiwan, etc.) tend to have higher correlations with other economics' performance. In other words, they are more independent of other economics to do well in order for them to do well.

  • We see that the US is by far the most independent of the 11 countries. This concurs with our conclusion because US is a consuming imports from other countries and have a well-rounded trade relation with them.

US Specific Correlations¶

  • The UK has the highest correlation with the US. This makes sense as its known that the two nations are heavily involved. From Wikipedia, we see that "The UK has always been the biggest foreign investor in the US and vice versa." (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom%E2%80%93United_States_relations). This is referred to as the "special relationship" between the US and UK.

  • Japan and US have a near-zero correlation, despite their good economic ties. This can be explained by Japan's economic troubles over the past decade. (http://qz.com/198458/zombies-once-destroyed-japans-economy-now-theyre-infecting-chinas/)

  • European (excluding UK) countries are all very closely tied, with correlation near 1 between each pair.

  • Despite these close ties, the correlations between France and the Netherlands and the US are much lower than that of Germany and Sweden. Any idea of an explanation for this?

  • Generally, the US has much less of a dependence on foreign nations than other countries.

Looking specifically at European countries¶

  • As we would expect, UK, France, Germany, Sweden, and the Netherlands corrrelate highly with each other.
  • Germany, Sweden, and the Netherlands all have the lowest correlation with the UK compared to other continental Enropean countries because UK is still not part of the eurozone.

A DataFrame built from these 12 timeseries contains a large amount of data. To analyze this data, we must look at it in a few different ways. That is. to "clean" this data we narrow down what we are looking at. First, we can build a matrix which displays the piecewise correlations between each pair of countries.¶

Creating the Directory Structure¶

First, create necessary directories to store our data in during future steps of the project. The directories are created as subdirectories within the directory this notebook resides in.

In [24]:

mkdir ./script ./data ./data/raw ./data/cleaned ./data/simulated ./visualizations
ls -r

Collecting the Data¶

Import the necessary Python libraries to collect data.

In [25]: 
import pandas as pd
import pandas.io.data as web
from pandas import Series, DataFrame
import datetime
from pandas.tools.plotting import scatter_matrix

Chose a period of ~2 years, a significant amount of data. Had to move start date back to 5/7/2010, as this is the earliest date for which Yahoo finance has closing price data for USA (surprisingly, Yahoo finance for all other countries had a much larger date range).

In [26]: 
start = datetime.datetime(2010, 5, 7)
end = datetime.datetime(2013, 1, 27)

Use pandas method "DataReader" to attain data directly from Yahoo Finance, allowing us to open project on any computer and access data through notebook. The data is stored directly into the format of a dataframe.

In [27]: 
a = web.DataReader('THD', 'yahoo', start, end)
a.head()
